
===================================================================
Variable inside and outside a loop
===================================================================

ASK: 

Do I need to remember something across iterations?

Yes → variable outside the loop (or initialized outside).
No → variable can be created inside the loop.


The Two Golden Rules

- Put the variable **outside** if you want to **remember** or **add up** data across the whole loop.

- Put the variable **inside** if you want a **fresh, clean start** for every single step.


Outside the Loop

The variable is created once before the loop begins.

- **Scope:** Accessible both inside the loop and after the loop finishes.
- **State/Accumulation:** Preserves its value across iterations. This is ideal for tracking sums, counts, or building up a list.
- **Performance:** Slightly more efficient because the program allocates memory for the variable only once. [[1](https://dev.to/realnamehidden1_61/should-try-catch-be-written-inside-or-outside-the-for-loop-and-sta
- ea3k21(https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43220002/does-c-remake-a-variable-defined-in-a
Inside the Loop

A new variable is created (and destroyed) during every single iteration.

- **Scope:** Only accessible within the block of that specific iteration. It is deleted when the loop resets and cannot be accessed after the loop ends.
- **State/Accumulation:** Resets every time the loop runs. It cannot hold onto data from the previous iteration.
- **Performance:** Slightly less efficient in heavy processes, as the computer must repeatedly allocate and deallocate memory


